other_spp_impact: The previous question was unclear. The halibut fishery has been effected by the changes in scientific evaluation of rockfish stocks (particularly yellow eye) which erroneously evaluated their populations at low levels which significantly changed fishermen's approach to harvesting halibut and other target species.  In regards to climate change, shifting migratory patterns of various species such as pyrozomes.  I think has had an effect on target species as we were pulling up black cod stuffed to the gills with them, this is purely anecdotal but it leads me to wonder what the shift in diet would have on black cod and their traditional prey species.
timing_change_descrp: Seasonal changes have been observed in the halibut fishery due to reduction of yellow eye quota. Fishermen successfully avoided yellow eye catches by shifting their fishing season from summer to winter/spring to fish in deeper water to avoid yellow eye habitat overlap. This has been documented in scientific papers but does not seem to be effected by climate change.
spp_neg: Salmon (stream habitat being devastated by drought, runoff and extreme weather conditions), herring (potentially shifting migration patterns north out of Canadian territory).
spp_pos: There is limited evidence that tuna migration patterns may shift north due to climate change increasing Canadian fishermen's ability to access stocks. The full effect of this will need to be closely monitored and recorded.
flexible_mgmt: Better communication from DFO federal. Better communications between Fisheries department and Oceans department (often they work at odds and disagree on fundamental dynamics). Better opportunities for DFO to celebrate and communicate their successes (right now they are not able to communicate their successes, only their failures) as this would add more confidence and trust in the department from the general public resulting possibly in better funding from politicians. And most of all: better funding for scientific stock assessment of Pacific species.
concern_future: I am concerned we will not balance our conservation, economic and social goals moving forward. Each pillar is necessary to keep our industry afloat and villainizing  each other (within the fishing community and towards DFO) will only serve to weaken us.

explanation: according to DFO the decrease in salmon returns in 2019 were due in part to climate change.  I would argue that warmer temperatures due to climate change and the subsequent loss of glacial water flows for salmon will cause further decrease in salmon abundance in BC and the US west coast
other_spp_impact: warmer water and uv rays are affecting feed for salmon in and around coastal and mid ocean waters.  Chronomids and other important sources of salmon feed are decreasing as a result of warmer waters due to climate change.  Also, higher water temperatures are affecting salmon spawning and up river migration as higher than normal water temperatures promote diseases.
range_change_descrp: Salmon stocks have been in decline on a steady basis since the late 90's.. Some of this is due to the fact that the Federal Government  has reduced the numbers of hatchery programs that were put in place in the 70's and 80's to mitigate the loss of habitat.  There were  millions of dollars in federal funds dedicated to the rebuilding of salmon stocks in BC,  Those commitments have been basically scrapped and we are seeing the results today.  During the 70's there was spending of $350 million dollars over 7 years to enhance BC salmon stocks.  The federal govt. has since abrogated its duty to Pacific Coast Salmon
spp_neg: Salmon and likely most other species to some degree
env_neg_mental: I have not observed any changes
flexible_mgmt: Federal long term commitment to fully funded increase in on grounds staffing to observe and report on a continuous cyclical basis to properly motor and identify and support coastal fisheries.  This would mean locating personnel to multiyear positions at facilities along coast with proper funding and staff levels.  Human encroachment on watersheds and estuaries has shown the need for increased effort through enhancement and other restorative measures to ensure the survival and rebuilding of BC salmon stocks. Its not just about checking for licences but further committing to uninterrupted continuos monitoring of coastal fisheries.
concern_future: At one time, there was a theory put forward that for every dollar spent on enhancement, there would be a twofold return.  Even if it was dollar for dollar we need to do something NOW!!!!

other_spp_impact: increased numbers of seals and sea lions plus their range up into rivers and onto spawning beds.    MARKED drop in kelp growth and amount throughout the coast causing less habitat for hearing, ling & rock cod and other species.
range_change_descrp: Far less salmon, ling and rock cod.
timing_change_descrp: DFO has drastically restricted the days of open fishing and delayed openings to later in the year until target species have passed the fishing areas.
spp_neg: All salmon fisheries. troll, seine, gillnet. I think about this each time I go down onto the docks or drive past the marinas. There once was hundreds of fishing vessels kept in great condition. Now there are few and many in poor condition as the economics of the industry is being destroyed.
flexible_mgmt: Listen more to the knowledgeable commercial fishers. There are some good ones within the overall group.    Expand the education of the management biologist  out onto the boats that are doing the harvesting.    Manage the fishery to science rather than politics.    Remove/kill off the seas and sea lions that are homesteading the estuaries, rivers and spawning beds. These are the 'junk yard' bears of the ocean and cause tremendous damage especially in watersheds with stocks of concern.    Stop catch and release fisheries including commercial and sport. Mainly force the retaining of most of the catch and once quota is taken get the gear out of the water. This is especially important with the chinook and coho fishing but really all species of salmon and ground fish.    Force all by catch to be retained aboard then sold with a split in the moneys between the fisher and stock management.    Do a better job of accurately documenting the sport catch similar to what is done with commercial trollers.    Remove the politics as best possible from  DFO management decisions.    Do more test fisheries in areas that have been closed for years to define stock make up and health.    Do more stream counts on watersheds in remote areas to define stock health.    Review the hatchery process and support and expand hatcheries that are efficient.    Do more stream enhancement in remote watersheds.    Expand the harvest and timing through a voluntary draw process to define stocks and timing of runs in normally not fished areas. And do this via quota harvest not derby.    Get the fish farms onto land based processes with good filtration of effluent.    Ensure plants processing farm fish have excellent filtration of effluent.    Turn all salmon fisheries into quota base not derby.    Define why kelp is disappearing from this coast. Has been going on for the  last 45 years starting in the south and progressing north. May be ocean warming but more likely other causes too? Get the blinders off the biologist that presently are locked in the Global warming explanation for everything. Too often people find what they believe is happening rather than what the actually causes are.    A fund needs to be developed to pay native fishers to start as deckhands in the fisheries to learn the business on select vessels. At some point these students would be able to run their own boats with financial assistance from the government.
concern_future: In particular the troll fishing could be a great cottage industry, especially frozen at sea troll caught fish. Getting more natives trained in this type of fishery with a lot of thought and restructuring of the access would accomplish a number of goats. But it would take planning, commitment and follow through.    I think the fish are there in harvest able numbers in a well thought out and managed harvest through. It would need to be done via quota along with some intelligent marketing of 'white linen' markets plus local marketing.     It requires people thinking 'out of the box'. I think it would be viable for a limited number of eventual native owned and operated vessel. But, it requires good planning and committed folks on all sides. They would need to be committed natives, knowledgeable committed fishers,  eager government personnel and  marketing folks.     A small group of people from each of these four groups would need to put the process together so they 'owned' it for a few years till it became a working enterprise.    I think eventually small cottage type entities are the future of the commercial salmon fishery. The old derby, best boats take all, is dead. Something new needs to emerge or the whole this whole green industry will disappear.

explanation: Less returning adult salmon.  Due to significantly reduced ocean survival. A series of Dry summers in northern bc have resulted in difficult salmon passage to spawning grounds. The overall population and the allowable catch has been significantly reduced because of climate change.
other_spp_impact: Increased predators especially seals and sea lions have had  significant effect on salmon and herring fishing.  It is much harder to target salmon in areas of high predators without damaging gear and losing catch. Herring fishing has to be altered to avoid the predators aswell.
range_change_descrp: Overall salmon population is down.  Successful returns are very isolated by region and species and timing.  There are both more record high and record low returns now than 30 years ago. The extremes seem to be greater and there also seems to be more variations region to region.
spp_neg: The long distance migratory species (salmon) and the species dependent on those species for food (resident killer whales) seem to be the hardest hit by climate change.  Salmon have a massive migration and depend on food to be in a certain area at certain stage of their life when they arrive.  If a region typically high in resources is depleted when they get to it, they don't seem to have the ability to alter their normal migration fast enough to not die before getting to the next good feeding area. Extremes in climate also create the perfect storm of food production in isolated circumstances which seems to contribute to certain salmon stocks hitting the jackpot and doing really well. The resident whales dependent on a steady stream of migratory salmon to feed on through out the year have no chance right now. They don't have the ability to feed on and store enough food from 1 successful salmon run to survive. They need more consistent average returns of this food source through out the year.  As fisherman the only way to survive now is to be able to move from region to region and participate in the bumper crop returns. You can no longer fish 1 region or area and expect consistent rerturns.
spp_pos: Certain regions of salmon have had extreme success because the food resources in those regions have increased (northern pacific stocks, Russia, and Brystol Bay).  Extremely long term, more areas will open up to salmon habitat in the glacial regions of northern climates as glaciers reseed.  Fisheries for localized populations will benefit from climate change but you will have to move from place to place in a global or huge scale.
flexible_mgmt: More data is the only thing that can help.  Continue research and testing and try and do even more.  Increased knowledge of our species and stocks are the only way forward.
concern_future: You have to be extremly adaptable in commercial fishing now.  You have to move region to region in season, month to month almost week to week.  This is hard for the fishing community to do, but it is necessary.

explanation: Water level has risen, less beach available.   Different predators show up, targeting commercial stocks. ( scoters, otters, green crab )  High acid water affect clam and oyster survival at spat size, so less stock available.  Eel grass invading lower levels of intertidal, so that part of beach off limit to harvest.  Loss of time on beach due to smaller, shorter tides, larger storms offshore push the tide up resulting in even higher and shorter tides some days.  Winds come up faster and stronger, making travel to beaches by boat more difficult and dangerous.
other_warmingoe_ex: Clams and oysters, spawning more, surviving less.
other_spp_impact: Invasive green crab consuming manila clams.  Surf scoter numbers have increased , consuming clams and  mussels.   Sea otters have arrived consuming clams and many other species.  On a positive note, otters have eaten most dungeness and rock crab so oyster survival has skyrocketed.
range_change_descrp: Species are moving north, so bi-valves are spawning more often on the northern limits of their range.  As well, clams and oysters are living further up the beach.  Unfortunately some higher beach is not well suited for those species, so overall range on individual beaches is shrinking.
timing_change_descrp: DFO has greatly reduced the time we are allowed to fish.  DFO has also changed regulations making it harder to fish during productive times.
spp_neg: All fisheries will be affected, some positively, some negatively.
flexible_mgmt: DFO tends to micromanage and constantly shrink management areas.   There are a lot of cover your ass regulations which keep managers from thinking of new and innovative approaches.  The costs to industry of observers , hail services and restrictive regulations are increasing while fishing opportunities and areas are shrinking.  Small coastal fishers can't afford these costs when considering a new fishery.
concern_future: The health of the oceans and fish stocks is a very complicated issue.  Many of your questions could have had both a positive and a negative response.   Many questions had multiple factors.  Global warming is definitely having an impact but at the same time for the same species so might regulations, markets, costs... etc.   Thank you for the opportunity to comment.

other_spp_impact: All the predators are eating our juvenile species including the otter population growing in the north and the urchin population in in steep decline in those areas    But as far as salmon the California de lion is the biggest problem for our species as well as the continued over crowding of our spawning beds by dfo allow too much fish to go up rivers    There is a delicate number needed for each run and over spawning is a terrible Solution

explanation: shorter or no openings to fish; worry by those controlling my access to fish has increased causing unnecessary reductions in fishing time just to be on the safe side.
other_spp_impact: Reduction of krill and kelp seems to have reduced the amount of feed for all herring eating fish?
range_change_descrp: Major reduction in all species of salmon and ling cod but this result is more tied to increased predation by major increased in seals and sea lions.
timing_change_descrp: The openings to fish have been drastically reduced from five to six months to more weeks now. Further, the areas I was allowed to fish in have been reduced even further than the time allowed. This has forced the fleet to fish on top of each other plus kept as off productive areas to catch fish. Ocean warming may be part of reduced catch but timing and area restrictions have resulted in far more negative catches that warm I believe.
spp_neg: Krill, herring, salmon, ling cod. Then rock fish and  halibut because sports fishers target these when they can't catch their target species. Then juvenile yellow eye face major negative numbers through bi catch when sports fishers fish the pinnacles for halibut.   All this is in a major complicated frame work that simple ocean warming is only a part though perhaps an important part but by no means the whole.  A simple questionnaire like this can't hope to detail all the negative impacts with these narrow questions.
spp_pos: prawns and crab seem to be doing well?
flexible_mgmt: Those tasked with managing the various fisheries should be forced to spend some time within the various commercial fisheries to understand just what it is they are managing. This knowledge in DFO in Canada has been totally lost over the decades as those staff within DFO that hold some of this knowledge have long ago retired.  How can anyone be expected to properly manage an industry they have little knowledge of how it works, grows, shrinks or can be sustained if they know little or nothing of the industry it's self?
concern_future: Unless and until we manage the predation as well as the prey there is no hope for fish populations. We have done some stupid things in years gone by but even worse things in recent decades around managing seals and sea lions. If we continue to ignore the increased numbers of these animal the salmon and ling cod abundance will be completely killed off. Global warming is a MUCH lower concern that predation for these two fishes.
